3 TRANSPORTATION
4 Reproduced and distributed under the direction of the Secretary of the Senate.
5 STATE OF MAINE
6 SENATE
7 132ND LEGISLATURE
8 FIRST SPECIAL SESSION
9 COMMITTEE AMENDMENT “ ” to S.P. 46, L.D. 29, “Resolve, to Require the
10 Department of Transportation to Implement the Recommendations of the Lower Road Rail
11 Use Advisory Council”
12 Amend the resolve by striking out the title and substituting the following:
13 'Resolve, to Require the Department of Transportation to Implement the
14 Recommendations of the Lower Road Rail Use Advisory Council and the Calais
15 Branch Rail Use Advisory Council'
16 Amend the resolve in the preamble by inserting after the 5th paragraph the following:
17 'Whereas, the Department of Transportation received letters of support from
18 communities along the section of the state-owned rail corridor known as the Calais Branch
19 requesting the formation of a rail corridor use advisory council; and
20 Whereas, the Calais Branch Rail Use Advisory Council convened and met over a
21 period of 8 months in 2024; and
22 Whereas, 10 of the 11 Calais Branch Rail Use Advisory Council members, with one
23 member abstaining, voted to recommend the interim conversion of the existing railroad
24 track to a multi-use trail; and'
25 Amend the resolve by inserting after section 1 the following:
26 'Sec. 2. Calais Branch rail trail recommendation. Resolved: That, consistent
27 with the majority recommendation of the Calais Branch Rail Use Advisory Council and
28 pursuant to the Maine Revised Statutes, Title 23, section 7107, the Department of
29 Transportation shall remove 12.26 miles of state-owned inactive existing railroad track
30 along the section known as the Calais Branch from the Route 214 intersection in Ayers
31 Junction in the Town of Pembroke to Route 1 in the City of Calais and replace the track
32 with a multi-use trail on the existing rail bed. The completed multi-use trail is interim in
33 nature, and the project to create the multi-use trail is subject to available funding resources,
34 permitting and municipal agreements.'
